<h2>Competition</h2>
<p>DC Robotics completely uses the <a href="http://vexrobotics.com" class="_confirm _blank">VEX Robotics</a> Platform.  This system provides a line of parts that somewhat resemble the pieces of an Erector Set, a challenging game to try to win, and competition to rival.  Teams from schools and neighborhood groups around the world meet at dozens of tournaments to find stellar robots and their budding engineers.  The game teams play changes every school-year to keep ingenuity fresh and give new teams a chance.  This year, the game is VEX Round-Up.  On the right, you can watch the video VEX provides to explain the basics.  To put it simply, there are four teams competing at a time, two teams per alliance.  Alliances work together to score plastic tubes (affectionately called 'donuts') on foot-high pillars.  After the match, the scores are calculated and teams are ranked for an elimination-style tournament.</p>

<h2>History</h2>

<p>In 2008, DC Robotics began when some parents donated $500 to start a robotics program at DC.  With startup capital, physics teacher Jim Crane took on the challenge of starting a robotics program in the DC High School.  After doing some research, Crane discussed the matter with some of his more prominent physics students to hear what they thought of launching, and participating in, a robotics program.  In the remainder of the 2008-2009 school year, those students tinkered with robot parts, seeing what they could do, aiming to build a flamethrower.</p>

