<p>The 2009-2010 school year saw the objective become what most would consider more typical as the program evolved into DC Knights team 1267 in the VEX Robotics Competition league.  With a shift in membership, efforts intensified in the spring, building toward DC's first tournament, to take place in March of 2010.  After a long night finishing the robot, team 1267 won the Driver Skills challenge, which qualified them for the World Championship in April.  This surprise victory raised the question as to whether or not the team would be able to go.  Eventually, everything was arranged and the team went.  Performance on the world stage was less than spectacular, but it showed that the DC Robotics program, still in pilot state, could excel in a global arena.</p>

<p>Looking to expand in the 2010-2011 school year, Program Director Jim Crane opened the program to anyone interested in joining.  The result, a group of 26 students, broke into four separate High School teams.  By the end of the first semester in December, those teams had already piled up nine trophies and qualified three of the four teams.  This school year was also the christening year of J-Term, a two week period in January in which students can particiapate in an internship or courses in less-traditional subjects.  The DC Robotics staff, now including Chemistry &amp; Biology Teacher, Laura Tyler, designed J-Term courses to teach the basics to new-comers and let experienced students work on their competition robots.  Later that month, DC Robotics launched the middle school program.</p>